== 4. FactHarbor's Unique Positioning ==

=== What Makes FactHarbor Different ===

|=Feature|=Traditional|=Automated (Speed)|=Crowdsourced|=**FactHarbor**
|**Verdict Type**|Categorical|NLI Class|Text note|**Probabilistic + Scenario-based**
|**Transparency**|Article explains|Black box|Varies|**Full reasoning chain**
|**Multi-Agent Debate**|None|None|None|**Yes (5-step MAD)**
|**Multi-Source Retrieval**|Manual|Yes (Factiverse)|No|**Yes (Wikipedia+Scholar+Web)**
|**Debate-Triggered Re-search**|No|No|No|**Priority #8 (ED2D pattern)**
|**Confidence**|None|Uncalibrated|None|**Stated with factors**
|**Contradiction Check**|Sometimes|Rarely|Never|**Mandatory**
|**Output Format**|Article|Score|Free text|**Structured Evidence Model**
|**Scalability**|Low|High|Medium|**High (AI + quality gates)**
|**Open Source**|No|Partial|Yes (X)|**Yes**

=== Key Differentiators ===

1. **Boundary-Based Analysis:** A claim isn't just "true" or "false"—its truth depends on the methodology and scope of the evidence.
1. **Evidence Landscape:** Shows where a claim holds, fails, and where reasonable disagreement exists.
1. **Transparent Reasoning:** Every step from claim → boundary → evidence → verdict is visible.
1. **Probabilistic Verdicts:** Not just labels, but likelihood ranges with explicit uncertainty factors
1. **Versioned Knowledge:** Updates tracked; evidence evolution visible
1. **Federated Model:** No single entity controls the narrative; nodes can synchronize

